##I'm overseas. There's only one clinic in Montreal, Canada, that can screen for the new coronavirus

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

Canadians who were once envied for being able to fly back to safety on evacuation flights could never have imagined that one day we would have to experience suspension of classes, forced closure of all public places, panic buying, and out of stock.

By Eileen

A month ago, no one thought we'd be in this mess.

On March 12, I was in Montreal waiting to see how the epidemic would play out. With regard to the suspension of classes, only part of the classes are suspended in certain schools where there are individual suspected cases. Schools in Richmond begin spring break a week earlier than in Ontario, with one week in public schools and two weeks in private schools from March 2. Spring break is basically a time when Canadians go on wild winter outings. So, on March 12, some of my friends and I began to worry about what might happen to the people who were coming back from all over the place.

The news that evening about whether the prime minister's wife tested positive for the virus was basically in the stage of suspicion. The first thing my mother said when we got home from work was that Trudo's wife had been diagnosed. I said, fake news. Now all news must find the original mainstream media, otherwise can not believe. Early the next morning, the news came that the prime minister's wife had been diagnosed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Canadian Prime Minister Trudo and his wife Sophie

Meanwhile, on the afternoon of March 12, there has been a run on toilet paper from supermarkets on friendagenda. A friend proudly told the group that the Costco in the suburbs at 2 p.m. was still full, and that his friends had bought everything with ease. Wait until 6 pm to go to the same Costco and empty the shelves.

On 13 March, it became clear to us in Montreal that the situation had taken a turn for the worse. Quebec's governor, Fran Ois Legault, announced tough anti-epidemic policies at a live news conference, this includes all day care, schools, preparatory courses in Quebec (the province's education system is the same as in France, with a two-year preparatory course before entering university) and universities that will be closed for at least two weeks. All libraries and community stadium will be closed until further notice. In fact, most schools were closed on March 13. The government will establish special day care for children of health workers and other essential service workers so that they can continue to work normally.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At Montreal Metro on Friday morning, March 13th, passengers were scarce | respondents

In addition, health authorities have restricted access to some hospitals and sanatoriums in Montreal. Not only that, for all the province's 70-year-old elderly, the governor also asked for home self-isolation to avoid the risk of infection. The governor said Quebec must learn from China's experience by analysing the data it has collected in its previous fight against the disease.

Subsequently, the Société de Transport de Montréal also announced that all of its employees would be banned from travelling outside the Richmond, both individually and for work, or they would have to be quarantined. The STM also says it will daily clean the surfaces most commonly used on subways and buses, including handrails, escalators, lifts and ticket machines.

Buying and stocking up, and no one's wearing a mask

After two days of hoarding, I finally had time to go to the supermarket last Saturday. Costco has been supplying disinfectant wipes to every customer entering its shopping cart for weeks.

March 14 into the supermarket, in addition to wipe the car disinfection paper, there are special hand disinfection paper. Costco, which canceled all its sample service, has placed sterile paper towels on the fresh freezer. Costco set aside a corner that day to distribute paper products. Toilet paper, kitchen paper and Napkins have been rationed. In the checkout area, staff also check each cart for overpurchases. In addition to the limited supply of paper supplies, bleach, disinfectant paper towels and liquid soap all out of stock.

Despite pictures of Costco's "retaliatory" restocking on facebook, virtually all the paper products in the supermarket were restricted on March 15, and sterilisation products are still out of stock. Everything from big box stores like Costco to neighborhood pharmacies is out of stock and restricted.

What is most puzzling, however, is that hundreds of people are crowding around a store to buy toilet paper, and none of them are wearing masks.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
People at Costco in Montreal buy toilet paper, but no one wears a mask

Montreal, a nervous hoarder, has no toilet paper to buy later, and masks are few and far between on the streets. The vast majority of people who happen to see masks on the road are ethnic Chinese.

Although locals do not wear masks, all pharmacies were out of stock more than a month ago. In the past, local Daigou have shipped masks home. Now, each big wechat group in the registration number from the domestic transport mask to Canada.

The city centre is empty

As tensions mount, Joe Beef, one of Montreal's most famous restaurants, said it would close indefinitely after closing on March 14 until it could resume operations. On the morning of March 15, Downtown Montreal was empty, and on the evening news, most restaurants in Chinatown would be closed from Monday. However, compared with these famous restaurants, which do not lack customers, it is very difficult for each small restaurant to survive in the street.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chinatown

I run a nearly 20-year-old Sushi restaurant in Montreal. The restaurant is in one of Montreal's most affluent neighborhoods. The guests are mainly residents of the community and the surrounding library, school and municipal staff. From Thursday to the weekend, the busiest time for business, customers have largely disappeared as schools have closed and the government has introduced a series of tough measures.

Next to my home there is a well-known Portuguese Roast Chicken restaurant, weekend dinner reservations need to be made, otherwise a hard to get. On the afternoon of March 13, the manager told me with a worried look on his face that all their reservations for the day had been cancelled, and the reason for the guests was that they were afraid of the virus. At present, they are discussing whether it is necessary to suspend business in order to reduce losses. On the evening of March 15, he ran into the owner of a roast chicken restaurant, who said he planned to keep only one employee, though not close the shop, while delivering his own food.

On March 15, the provincial government of Quebec announced that all bars, nightclubs, buffets and other places were forcibly closed. The Minister of Public Health in Quebec, Horacio Arruda, has insisted that closing public places such as bars is an order, not a recommendation. On the afternoon of March 15, a friend had told the Quebec Lottery Bureau to go to his bar and force the machine to close. In addition, for restaurants that do not have to close, the government recommends that restaurants only open half of their seats and require dining chairs to be placed at least one meter apart.

"It's like we're at war. "

As of March 16,436 cases had been confirmed in Canada, including 50 in Richmond.

Medical staff at Jewish General, one of Quebec's four new Crown Treatment Hospitals, in Downtown Montreal, said they were preparing for a "big wave" of possible new crown patients. It is reported that the Jewish hospital has 87 beds can accommodate new crown patients. "It's like we are in a situation of war, " Francine Dupuis, deputy director of Health in Montreal, said at a news conference

Montreal currently has only one screening clinic for COVID-19, but Dupuis said Montreal plans to open two more clinics to relieve pressure on hospitals. But she acknowledged that if there were an outbreak, there would be little the hospital could do.

Speaking to the nation on March 16, Canadian Prime Minister Trudo said Canada would ban most foreign nationals from entering the country.

Now, I can only hope the outbreak doesn't break out here..
